column13: 1,215,644. D.C. chopper circuit. W. BROOKS. 17 April, 1968 [6 June, 1967], No. 18185/68. Heading H3T. A D.C. chopper circuit utilizing resonance commutation comprises a silicon-controlled rectifier SCR-1 arranged to supply pulsed D.C. to a load 12, e.g. a shift register. In operation, a positive pulse to SCR-1 when push switch 14 is closed, fires it and it remains ON until commutated off, to supply load 12. An external signal to shift is applied to transformer T-1 which triggers SCR-2. SCR-2 fires and short circuits a series resonance circuit L-1 C-1, and current from a capacitor C-1 flows to and fro in the loop, capacitor C-1 being initially charged via R-6. During the second half cycle of oscillation in the loop current cannot flow through SCR-2 and goes instead from L1, via diodes Dl, D2 to C1. The voltage drop across D2 reverse biases SCR-1 and shuts it off, interrupting the current to the load. In addition the voltage on bus 15 exceeds that in bus 10 and SCR-2 cuts off. A trigger pulse is then applied to a transformer T-2 to gate SCR-1 and turn it ON again to supply the load. To recharge C-1 at the end of the cycle a circuit C2, R5, L17 of transformer T-3 is placed across SCR-1. When SCR-1 fires at conclusion of cycle its voltage drop goes to near zero and this change in voltage causes T-3 to gate SCR-3, via a diode D-3, thus firing it which recharges C1. Thus when SCR-1 fires SCR-3 also fires. When SCR-2 is then fired and the resonant circuit L-1, C-1 later turns off SCR-2, no current can pass to SCR-3 which shuts off.

column13: 1,194,042. Displays: shift registers. W. BROOKS. 9 June, 1967 [13 June, 1966], No. 26772/67. Heading G4H, G4C. The stages of an electronic shift register control respective display elements by means of silicon-controlled-rectifiers. In the shift register of Fig. 7, having data input at 86, shift pulses at 90 reset transfluxors 71-77 to "zero". Those not already at "zero" charge following capacitors 94 to set the respective next transfluxors to "one". Each cycle of an oscillator 70 non-destructively reads out the transfluxor state via silicon-controlledrectifiers 61-67 to lamps 11-17. In the shift register of Fig. 8, an input of "one" at 104 causes silicon-controlled rectifier 131 to fire, lighting lamp 111, discharging capacitor 161 and charging capacitor 141. A shift pulse opening switch 103 cuts off S.C.R. 131 so that capacitor 141 starts to discharge via lamp 111. The shift pulse ends before this discharge has proceeded far whereupon capacitor 141 charges capacitor 161 causing siliconcontrolled-rectifier 132 of the second stage of the register to fire. The next shift pulse cuts off both S.C.R's 131, 132 and so on. Had the input at 104 been "zero", S.C.R. 131 would not have fired, capacitor 141 would not have charged so it could not subsequently discharge to fire S.C.R. 132 via capacitor 161. The "lamps" above may each be a bar consisting of several neon tubes or a single fluorescent lamp, the bars being arranged in a figuregram or &c. to permit a selected numeral or letter or &c. to be built up by energizing selected bars. Alter natively, the lamps may illuminate respective masks for optical projection on to a screen. A row of figuregrams may be controlled ,by respective shift registers connected in series. Alternatively, each row of an elongated matrix of individual lamps may be controlled by a respective shift register to allow a message to be displayed and moved along. The data and shift input switches 86, 90, 104, 103 may be controlled by stepping switches or other shift registers. Input may be manual or on punched tape or cards. Blue, green and red lamps may be used at each lamp position and scanned in sequence.

Audio transfer, storage and playback system
column13: A system for providing recorded audio programming in digital form, comprising a computer server capable of digitally recording, holding and uploading audio programming in either musical or voice formats and able to transmit such modulated digital data in a time-compressed, encrypted and encoded manner through a wireless transmission, where the data is received using RF electronics, then stored for transfer to a combination audio receiver/player/data storage device. This storage device comprises a readable/writable memory storage mechanism (e.g., disk drive, hard drive, memory or flash card system) and playback or player feature interfaced with a mobile or fixed site RF receiver capable of receiving wireless transmissions. As the transmissions are received, the programming data is demodulated and stored in digital form and then converted to "real time" audio one file at a time, utilizing a digital-to-analog converter, and played back to the listener.

column12: INFORMATION AND ENTERTAINMENT PROGRAMMING BROADCAST SYSTEM AND DEVICE
column13: A system for providing entertainment and/or information programming to a plurality of users in a uniquely useful form. The system comprises a point of origin content provider (11) compiling programming into encoded and segmented data files via a predetermined protocol and a computer server (2) capable of digitally recording, uploading, and holding the data files in digital form representing sensory perceptible expressions. The system further includes a means of transmitting the digital data (15) in a time-compressed and possibly encrypted manner and a user controlled apparatus appropriate to the transmission means and having means to receive and store the encoded, compressed digital data files and a means to playback the data files. As the transmissions are received, the appropriate data files are extracted, compiled into discrete data files, possibly watermarked and stored in digital form. Since the predetermined protocol is programmed into the user-controlled apparatus, the data files can be converted to sensory perceptible entertainment and/or information one file at a time.

column13: 775,688. Knitting. BELMONT THROWING CORPORATION. Aug. 4, 1954, No. 22628/54. Class 74 (2). [Also in Group IX] A knitted fabric, e.g. a patterned elastic stocking, has areas knitted of differently coloured polyamide or polyester yarns, each yarn being formed from two loosely intertwisted, e.g. multifilament, strands, after twisting each strand (but in opposite direction) a plurality of turns, setting, dyeing, twisting an additional plurality of turns in the same direction, setting and shrinking, then, (if desired), imparting additional twist, followed by setting and drying and, in either event, finally untwisting to substantially zero twist or beyond. In Fig. 1, the top or welt 12, heel pocket 14, foot 15, toe pocket 16 and leg areas 13g, 13h are knitted from a coloured body yarn. column12: Method of removing a ceramic coating
column13: A method of removing a ceramic coating, such as a thermal barrier coating (TBC) of yttria-stabilized zirconia (YSZ), from the surface of a component, such as a gas turbine engine component. The method generally entails subjecting the ceramic coating to an aqueous solution of ammonium bifluoride, optionally containing a wetting agent, such as by immersing the component in the solution while maintained at an elevated temperature. Using the method of the invention, a ceramic coating can be completely removed from the component and any cooling holes, with essentially no degradation of the bond coat.

column12: MEANS OF SUPPLYING GASEOUS FUEL FOR POWER, ETC.
Method of constructing septic system including pipe support
column13: A method includes placing pipe stands to support waste-conveying pipes in a trench in a septic system. The pipe stands are preferably flat bowtie-shaped sheets (preferably polymeric) folded to form stable pipe supports. Holes or notches are formed that align when the sheet is folded, thus providing stable support for a horizontal pipe when the panels' bottom edges rest on the ground. Modified versions include: folding a fold-out foot in the panels for engaging soft soil, forming fold-out dispersing flanges for dispersing waste dropped from the pipe, driving stakes into soft soil for stability, punching-out rings or multiple holes for supporting different sized pipes, stabilizing opposing panels in the sheet to fixedly maintain their spacing, forming a feature for receiving a grounded wire stake, and/or providing a bias from the living hinge of the fold line causing frictional gripping of the pipe. Many versions can be used in different orientations.

column13: 24,688. Sayers, W. B. Nov. 7. Elastic-fluid turbines.-Relates to turbines of the kind described in Specification No. 297, A.D. 1906, in which the motive fluid is caused to pass through the motor in a helical path partly in the periphery of the rotor and partly in the adjacent surface of the stator, and consists in utilizing the fluid leaking between the rotor and stator. Leakage passages a, a<1>, Figs. 1 and 2, of gradially increasing crosssectional area, are formed on the inner peripheral surface b of the stator adjacent to the side of the " reversing chambers" c and rotor buckets, the passage a finally exhausting into a " reversing "chamber " c<1> of lower pressure, whereby the leakage fluid does useful work. The leakage passage a<1> is connected to a " reversing chamber " c<2> by way of a curved passage a<2>. One or more auxiliary leakage passages may be arranged outside those described for collecting any further lateral leakage and delivering into chambers at still lower pressure. Corresponding passages on opposite sides may be connected together.

5192. Brooks, W. J. March 1. Cigar cutters.-A thin blade S is hinged to a lever D and is actuated thereby to cut the tip of a cigar inserted in the hole H made in the two sides of the member B. The lever D is hinged to B at P by means of a plate E riveted or soldered thereto, and is extended beyond the blade joint to increase the leverage. The lever and body B may be roughened, engraved, or perforated to give a grip for the fingers. A hole J and a slot J<1> in the plate E may serve for attachment to a key-ring or the like. column12: METHOD OF SELECTIVELY STRIPPING AN ENGINE-RUN CERAMIC COATING
column13: A process for selectively stripping a coating from a component of a turbomachine, and particularly a coating having a ceramic matrix that contains metallic particles dispersed therein that render the coating more difficult to remove from the component after the component has been subjected to elevated temperatures during operation of the turbomachine. The process generally includes immersing the component in an aqueous solution containing ferric chloride, nitric acid, and phosphoric acid, for a duration sufficient to attack the metallic particles in the coating. The component is then removed from the aqueous solution and its surface rinsed of the aqueous solution. The immersing and removing steps are then sequentially repeated a sufficient number of times to sufficiently attack the metallic particles to enable the coating to be mechanically removed from the component.

column12: Improvements relating to slip control apparatus
column13: 989,119. Vehicle brakes. WESTING- HOUSE BRAKE & SIGNAL CO. Ltd. May 6, 1963 [May 11, 1962], No. 18161/62. Heading F2F. [Also in Divisions B7, G1 and H3] Apparatus for preventing excessive slipping between one or more members of a first body engaging a second body on a surface on which forces are exerted via the members to tend to produce a change of speed of the first body comprises means for deriving respective signals representative of the peripheral velocities of the members, selective means for selecting in accordance with the relative magnitudes thereof that one of the signals which corresponds to the member which slips least and respective comparison means for comparing each signal with the signal thus selected to give indication of slip between a member or members and the surface being excessive with means responsive to such indication for adjusting the force applied via the member or members in such a sense as to tend to reduce the slip. As shown compressed air from a compressor is applied to a storage reservoir 2 the output pipe 3 of which is connected through a driver's valve 5 and pipes 6, 7 to electro pneumatic valves 17, 18. The latter are connected respectively to the front and rear brake cylinders 8, 10 and 9, 11. Associated with each wheel is a generator 12, 13, 14, 15, e.g. a variable reluctance toothed wheel generator which induces a voltage in a coil of a permanent magnet the frequency of which is proportional to the angular velocity of the wheel. A diode pump circuit, Fig. 3, produces at the point A a voltage proportional to the angular velocity of the wheel. The respective voltages produced by the generators 14, 15 are then compared by a comparison amplifier circuit comprising transistors T2, T3 and diode D3 which along with the corresponding transistors and diode in the other half of the circuit makes available at the point B whichever of the signals derived from the two diode pumps is the greater. The signal at B is fed to the transistor T2 and also to the corresponding transistor to produce at C a signal which represents any difference that exists between the angular velocity of the wheel associated with that circuit and the greater value of angular velocity represented by the signal at B. This difference signal is then fed to the transistor T4 which is so biased as to permit energization thereof by signals above a predetermined value which corresponds to the amount of slip which can occur before the slip is regarded as excessive. The transistor T4 when energized operates a relay RL1 which is connected via a diode D5 to the transistor in the circuit corresponding to the other front wheel. Energization of relay RL1 or RL2 causes the valve 17 or 18, as the case may be, to reduce the pressure in the corresponding front or rear brake cylinders. A network R4, R5, D4, C3 is effective as a delay storage network to permit a fixed rate of delay of the last received signal in the event of all wheels locking at once so as to ensure that a reference signal is always available for the comparison amplifiers. If the nearside and offside wheels are to be compared provision may be made to compensate for unequal angular velocities arising from cornering. Such compensation may be a signal applied to the apparatus indicative of the linear velocity of the vehicle and the radius of the turning circle or alternatively means may be provided to render the apparatus inoperative in the event of the vehicle traversing a turning circle of less than a predetermined radius, such an amount being indicated by the steering wheel. The invention may be applied to a wheeled road vehicle for the purpose of preventing wheel spin during acceleration. If the angular velocity of the two compared wheels differs by more than a predetermined amount the driving force may be relieved on all driven wheels, e.g. by throttling back the engine, easing the clutch or braking the driving wheels or at least the wheel whose angular velocity is excessive. If only the driving wheel on one side of the vehicle is unable to grip means may be effective to lock the differential. The invention may also be employed for detecting a difference in angular velocity of wheels arising from a difference in radius caused by the tyre on one becoming defective due to a puncture or leaking air valve. This indication may energize a light or other warning means. The invention may also be applied to metal rolling mills, the second body being a sheet of metal and the members being the rollers of the mill.

column13: An article carrier for a bicycle conforms to the shape of a bicycle and has substantially the same dimensions as the bicycle frame. The article carrier includes a waterproof base and cover which are removably assembled to protect items carried within the article carrier.

The linkage connects a first bicycle (A) to a second bicycle (B), and enables the first bicycle to have steering control over the second. The linkage allows both bicycles to lean so as to maintain balance by articulation of links 3 and 6 on bearings 1 and 2 and joints 4, 5 and 7. The linkage provides for the steering of the second bicycle (B) bicycle to follow the direction of the first bicycle (A) either by: (a) fixing the steering of bicycle B to the frame of bicycle A via link 3 or (b) by allowing bicycle B steering rotation at joint 4 and arranging for joint 7 to be positioned ahead of the steering axis of bicycle B so as to allow the steering of bicycle B to castor relative to the frame of bicycle A. By making some or all of the bearings and joints detachable, the bicycles can be used or stored separately as required. <IMAGE>

column12: Chemical removal of a chromium oxide coating from an article
column13: A chromium oxide coating is removed from a surface of an article by cleaning the article in an alkaline degreasing/rust removal solution at a degreasing/rust removal temperature of from about 180°F to about 200°F, scale conditioning the article in an alkaline permanganate conditioning solution at a scale-conditioning temperature of from about 160°F to about 200°F and contacting the article with an acidic stripping solution comprising hydrochloric acid and an etching inhibitor at a stripping temperature of from about 130°F to about 140°F.

column12: VORRICHTUNG ZUR ABGABE EINES FLUESSIGEN MEHRKOMPONENTEN-ERZEUGNISSES
Fuel grain for spherical boost-sustain rocket motor
column13: A spherical solid rocket motor for delivering boost-sustain, thrust-time performance and having a fuel grain with eight slots, at the forward end of the fuel grain, and eight star point segments forming regressive burning surface configurations. The fuel grain also has eight segments, with parallel sides, positioned between the star point segments to provide a large burning surface for boost and a sharp transition from boost to sustain operation.

column12: Improvements in Machinery for Finishing Lasso Rings and other Metal Rings of a like kind.
column13: 2459. Brooks, J. W. Jan. 31. Milling ; lathes ; chucks. -Relates to an apparatus for machining lasso rings automatically. The rings are first turned on their peripheries and sides and are then finished inside by a milling-tool. The two operations may be performed consecutively in one machine. Fig. 4 shows a vertical section through the turning portion of the machine. The ring E is held by a chuck A on a revolving spindle A'. The chuck, as shown separately in Figs. 7 and 8, consists of four or more conical fingers a<1>, a<2>, a<3>, a<4>, which are drawn together by a rubber ring a<8>, and are expanded by a conical spindle F, Fig. 4, so as to hold the ring in the groove a<7>. The chuck A and the spindle F are raised and lowered by cams on the shaft D and levers c<4> and f<1> respec. tively. The outside of the ring is turned by a tool h<1>, Fig. 6, held in a slide H, which is advanced by a lever h<4> driven by a cam on the shaft D. As the outside of a ring is finished the chuck collapses, and is raised clear to allow another ring to be placed in position. A pile of ring castings is supported between angular uprights P, I<2>, shown in plan in Fig. 18, and the lowermost ring is pushed into position below the chuck A by a slide J actuated by a lever j<1> and a cam on the shaft D. The rings pass along guides formed by plates g<1>,g<2>, g<4>, g<5>, shown to a larger scale in Fig. 5, and the ring which has been turned on the outside is pushed on by the next ring into position to be milled on the inside. The ring is gripped by jaws M<1>, M<2>, Fig. 18, of which M<1> is advanced by a cam m<3>, and M<2> is set in a fixed position by a screw m<1>. The tool for milling the inside of the ring is of exactly similar construction to the chuck A and is operated in the same way, milling-edges being formed in the groove a<7>. As an alternative, a pair of milling-bosses N<1>, N<2>, Fig. 23, with cutting- edges n<1>, n<2>, may be used to machine the insides of the rings. The chuck A may be used to hold the rings when turning them up by hand in an ordinary lathe, a plate being fixed on the slide-rest to stop the ring at the groove a'.

column12: Optical communications system and method for transmitting information through a single optical waveguide
column13: An optical communication system for communicating information. The systems includes a source of continuous wave laser light and one or more acoustic beams whcih are frequency or amplitude modulated by data. The laser light beam and the acoustic beams are input to an acousto-optical modulator for producing an undiffracted laser light beam and one or more diffracted laser light beams. The diffracted laser light beams are frequently shifted from the undiffracted laser light beam and contain the data to be transmitted. The diffracted and undiffracted beams are combined and transmitted over an optical fiber for demodulation at a distant location by a receiver. The receiver includes a photodiode which heterodynes the diffracted and undiffracted beams and produces signals having the frequencies of the acoustic beams. Tuning circuitry separates the signals and demodulators reconstruct the data transmitted. By using two such communication systems with a single optical fiber and by allocating the available bandwidth, simultaneous, bidirectional multi-channel communications are achieved.

column13: 7643. Sayers, W. B. March 30. Elastic-fluid turbines.-Relates to turbines of the type described in Specification No. 297, A.D. 1906, in which buckets are formed on the periphery of a rotor, and guide-passages are arranged in a surrounding stator in such a way that the steam traverses a forwardly - progressing spiral path between the inlet and exhaust ports. The improvement lies in providing additional guide-passages in the stator so that part of the steam traverses a rearwardlyprogressing spiral path. The Figure shows a group of rotor buckets and two inlets a, a<1>. Passages c in the stator lead the steam exhausting from one side of the buckets back again to impact repeatedly before reaching the exhausts b, b<1>. Similar passages c<1> are arranged to lead steam in a rearward direction with repeated impacts until the exhausts b<1>, b are reached. The construction prevents backward leakage between inlets and exhaust ports, and increases the effective extent of rotor periphery. No stagnant steam exists in the buckets to absorb the energy of the fresh steam. The number of inlets and outlets is not restricted to two.

Pipe stands support waste-conveying pipes in a trench in a septic system. The pipe stands are preferably flat bowtie-shaped sheets (preferably polymeric). Holes or notches are formed that align when the sheet is folded, thus providing stable support for a horizontal pipe when the panels' bottom edges rest on the ground. Modified versions include panels having: a fold-out foot for engaging soft soil, a fold-out dispersing flange for dispersing waste dropped from the pipe, a stake for driving into soft soil, punch-out rings or multiple holes for supporting different sized pipes, stabilizers between the panels that fixedly maintain their spacing, a feature for receiving a grounded wire stake, and/or bias from the living hinge of the fold line causing frictional gripping of the pipe. Many versions can be used in different orientations. Also, the present pipe stand can be used to support pipes and wires hanging from overhead rafters.

column12: Use of carbon dioxide to reduce the pH in circulating hard water
column13: The disclosure teaches a method of retarding the loss of carbon dioxide from a circulating water system by means of quaternary ammonium compounds having at least one hydrocarbon radical containing twelve or more carbon atoms or at least two hydrocarbon radicals each containing seven or more carbon atoms. In the method an effective amount of a suitable quaternary ammonium compound is added to the water in the system, surprisingly slowing the rate of loss of carbon dioxide from the water. Carbon dioxide is added to the water as needed to maintain the desired pH. The method provides an advantageous alternative to using stronger and more hazardous acids in maintaining a lowered pH in circulating water systems, for example, in heat exchange systems that utilize cooling towers.

column13: An orthotic support system is embodied as cooperating seat and back cushion elements for assembly into a wheelchair frame. These cushion elements are custom-fitted to the individual patient by injecting an incipiently reacting and foaming, fluorocarbon-blown polyurethane chemical system into the space between a rigid mold box and an elastic membrane which is fitted over the open face of the mold box and which is deformably engaged by the appropriate portions of the patient's torso. The foaming mixture is injected in predetermined excess volume and expands against the physical resistance of the patient's body where contact is made with the corresponding regions of the elastic membrane; and this forcible engagement produces selective densification of the foam where a high degree of body support is required. Elsewhere, the foam expands more freely and stretchably inflates the membrane to generate graduatedly less dense regions matably contoured to fit or partially embrace the patient. For body alignment purposes, specialized bolsters are integrally formed in the cushion elements.

column13: A backup assembly is provided for backing up a seal assembly that seals a gap between two components of a joint assembly. The spring element may be a garter spring, and the elastomer may be over-molded around the spring. The elastomer, spring element, and rings form an annular backup ring. The backup assembly may be employed in a seal assembly for sealing a gap between two components of a joint assembly. The seal assembly may include a diaphragm seal component, and the backup assembly operates to provide backup and extrusion resistance for the seal component.

column13: 24,687. Sayers, W. B. Nov. 7. Elastic-fluid turbines. - Relates to the special construction of fixed and running blades for turbines of the kind in which the motive fluid is caused to follow a helical path partly in the periphery of the rotor, and partly in the adjacent surface of the stator. The rotor blades a are formed with curved outer edges, which are not symmetrical. The blades are bound together by a support n. The motive fluid enters the blades between the edges b c and is discharged between the edges d e, so that it follows an approximately semicircular path. The inlet portions of the blades form an angle a, Fig. 3, with a tangent to the rotor periphery ; this angle is less than the angle # formed by the outlet portions of the blades. The construction of the standing blades is such that the fluid emerging from a certain number of rotor blades is passed across to the inlet sides of rotor blades situated further forward. The direction of flow is indicated by arrows. The edges g h and i j are shaped similarly to the adjacent edges of the rotor buckets. The part situated between the points g i m, Fig 2, is approximately plane, radial, and centrally situated relatively to the rotor buckets. The part g h k is bent over and makes an acute angle with the periphery of the rotor. The part i j m is approximately radial. The distances between the standing blades increase progressively to alow for expansive working. Specification No. 297, A.D. 1906, is referred to.

column12: A Device for Securing the Safety of the Operator when Starting the Engine of a Motor Car.
column13: 27,961. Brooks, W. J. Dec. 23. Motor road vehicles.- The starting-handle for the motor is interlocked with the change-speed mechanism, clutch, or the like, so that it cannot be brought into action unless the motor is disconnected from the wheels ; the mechanism may also retard the spark and relieve the compression. In the form shown in Figs. 1, 2, and 3, the starting- shaft S is provided with a collar A or the equivalent, which may pass the notch in the locking-member B, as shown in Fig. 2, when the shaft is displaced longitudinally to engage the engine shaft. The member B is displaced at right-angles to the axis of the shaft, and is so connected to the changespeed lever or the like that it is in the position shown in Fig. 2 only when the change-lever is in the neutral position. If the change-lever is in gear, the lips L prevent operation of the starting-handle, as shown in Fig. 3. The locking-member may be pivoted and act in a similar way, and the lips L may be enlarged or even arranged to encircle the collar, as shown in Fig. 10. In a modified form, the locking-member engages the clutch at the inner end of the starting-shaft. In the form shown in Fig. 16, the collar A is formed on a sleeve A<1> connected to the shaft S by a slot b and pin a. The collar A is not free to move axially, and is formed with a notch with which the locking-piece B may engage, the locking-piece being also notched. The shaft S, although it can be moved longitudinally, cannot be rotated unless the locking-piece is in a suitable position with the engine disconnected from the road wheels. The locking-piece in this case may have a sliding motion. In another form the locking-piece is in the form of a bolt sliding at right-angles to the shaft and operated from a cranked spindle. The locking-member may be connected to the change-speed lever, clutch, &c. by link-work or flexible connexions. In order to retard the spark and relieve the compression, some part of the connecting link-work may be formed with a swelling e, Fig. 24, which raises a rod j, against the resistance of spring k when the starting-handle is unlocked, the rod being connected to the spark-advance and valves.

column12: OPTICAL COMMUNICATIONS SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR TRANSMITTING INFORMATION THROUGH A SINGLE OPTICAL WAVEGUIDE.
column13: Système de communication optique servant à communiquer des informations. Ledit système comprend une source de lumière laser à ondes continues (30) et un ou plusieurs faisceaux acoustiques (51) qui sont modulés en fréquence ou en amplitude par des données. Le faisceau de lumière laser et les faisceaux acoustiques sont introduits dans un modulateur acousto-optique (50) servant à produire un faisceau de lumière laser non difracté et un ou plusieurs faisceaux de lumière laser difractés (52). Les faisceaux de lumière laser difractés sont décalés en fréquence du faisceau de lumière laser non difracté et contiennent les données à transmettre. Les faisceaux difractés et non difractés sont combinés (60) et transmis par l'intermédiaire d'une fibre optique (16), afin d'être démodulés par un récepteur à un emplacement situé à distance. Ledit récepteur comprend une photodiode (70) mélangeant les faisceaux difractés et non difractés et produisant des signaux possédant les fréquences des faisceaux acoustiques. Un circuit de syntonisation (74) sépare les signaux et des modulateurs (80) reconstruisent les données transmises. L'utilisation de deux systèmes de communication semblables avec une fibre optique unique et l'affectation de la largeur de bande disponible permettent de réaliser des commnunications simultanées, bidirectionnelles et à canaux multiples.

column12: TUBULAR ARTICLES OF BIAXIALLY ORIENTED POLYMERS
column13: A method of producing a tubular article, such as a can body or a bottle, of a biaxially oriented crystallisable thermoplastic polymer such as polyethylene terephthalate from a tubular article of smaller dimensions, such as a preform, having at least one open end, comprises heating the smaller tubular article to a temperature above the glass transition temperature but below the melting temperature of the polymer, stretching the tubular article axially by mechanical means such as an extending push rod (122) or a drawing chuk element, and simultaneously or sequentiall stretching the tubular article both axially and transversely by internal fluid pressure introduced through the open end (13), without any external mould or other external constraint. The stretched and biaxially oriented article (10) may be subsequently heated further to anneal the polymer and thereafter cooled before removal from the stretching apparatus, the internal pressure being reduced during such annealing and cooling. For polyethylene terephthalate, the stretching temperature is from 75oC to 120oC and the internal fluid pressure from 7 to 15 bars, while the annealing temperature is from 110oC to 240oC and the reduced internal fluid pressure used during annealing and/or cooling is from 2 to 4 bars.

column12: OPTICAL COMMUNICATIONS SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR TRANSMITTING INFORMATION THROUGH A SINGLE OPTICAL WAVEGUIDE
column13: An optical communication system for communicating information. The system includes a source of continuous wave laser light (30) and one or more acoustic beams (51) which are frequency or amplitude modulated by data. The laser light beam and the acoustic beams are input to an acousto-optical modulator (50) for producing an undiffracted laser light beam and one or more diffracted laser light beams (52). The diffracted laser light beams are frequency shifted from the undiffracted laser light beam and contain the data to be transmitted. The diffracted and undiffracted beams are combined (60), and transmitted over an optical fiber (16) for demodulation at a distant location by a receiver. The receiver includes a photodiode (70) which heterodynes the diffracted and undiffracted beams and produces signals having the frequencies of the acoustic beams. Tuning circuitry (74) separates the signals and demodulators (80) reconstruct the data transmitted. By using two such communication systems with a single optical fiber and by allocating the available bandwidth, simultaneous, bidirectional multi-channel communications are achieved.

column12: Mechanism for eliminating need for flash memory in software RAID
column13: A method and mechanism for booting an operating system in a Redundant Arrays of Independent Disks (RAID) is disclosed. The method includes: searching for a copy of a RAID driver on at least one boot partition of a disk in the disk array, wherein copies of the RAID driver are stored in boot partitions of at least two of the disks in the disk array; and loading the RAID driver, if the RAID driver is found. In the preferred embodiment, the boot partitions of the disks are searched until a working copy of the RAID driver is found. The RAID driver is loaded and the RAID implemented. The operating system may then be booted. In this manner, the need for a Flash memory device for storing the RAID driver is eliminated. The method and mechanism can be implemented in existing systems not designed to support software RAID.

column13: 13,243. Murray, W. B. June 7. Combined electrical and mechanical systems; non - automatic; electrical systems, non - auto - matic.-Each section of track is provided with a ramp formed of two insulated sections reversely inclined so as to co-operate with apparatus as described in Specification 13,242/13, and each section of the ramp is connected and disconnected from a source of energy by contacts on switches controlled by the semaphore signals, and the circuit to the section first engaged by a train contact also passes through a switch which is opened shortly after the circuit is completed by a train over that section of ramp. An auxiliary ramp is also provided by which the train is stopped if the signal just passed has not been returned to danger or if the track relay for the section in which the train is, has not opened its local contacts. Fig. 1 shows a length of track for traffic from right to left divided into insulated sections A, B, C, D with three-position semaphore signals 12<a>, 12<b>, 12<c> manually or electrically operated for each section and ramps 4 at the exit end of each section the circuits to which are controlled by track relays 15, contact member 21 on the semaphore, and contacts 30, 31 on a spindle 27 controlled by the semaphore and by an electro-magnetic detent 36. The ramps 4 have two insulated conducting-portions 6, 5 and a member 8 at each end which serves to raise slightly the collecting-shoe on the engine. The portions 6, 5 are inclined upwards towards the insulating-point between them, so that the engine-shoe is first raised and then falls while passing over the ramp, and does or does not receive current from the portions 6, 5 according to the state of the sections of track ahead, the signals and brakes being operated and controlled as described in Specification 13,242/13, according to the energizing or otherwise of the magnets 103<1>, 163 on the train. When the section A only is occupied, the signal 12<a> is at danger, signal 12<b> at caution, and signal 12<c> at clear. Under these circumstances, a train on section D about to pass into section C engages the ramp 6 and receives current from the battery 19 through the closed contacts 20 of the energized relay 15, segment 21, wire 41, magnet 38, and contact 31, the rail 1 serving as return conductor. The magnet 38 withdraws the detent 36 and allows the spindle 27 to rotate slowly under control of a dash-pot, thus opening the circuit of the ramp 6 at the contact 31 but not before the train has passed clear of the ramp section 6. At ramp 5 current is received by the engine from battery 19 through segment 21 as above and thence by wire 44. The engine thus receives current from both parts of the ramp. As soon as the train has passed into the section C the signal 12<c> should be set to danger, thus restoring the spindle 27 to close the contact 30 in the circuit to the ramp 45, which then energizes the engine apparatus on passing, but if the signal is not replaced, the train is stopped. The train on section C should de-energize the relay 15, which opens the circuit to the ramps 5, 6 in its rear. With the signal 12b at caution, the ramp 6 is energized as previously described, but the ramp 5 is cut out of circuit by the insulated portion of the segment 21. Fig. 2 shows an alternative arrangement for connexion of the ramp 45, which is energized from a battery 50 when the track relay 15 is de-energized while this battery is disconnected therefrom and connected to the segment 21 when the relay is energized. By this means, the train is stopped if the armature of relay 15 sticks or is held up by leakage currents.

column12: Improvements in or relating to Turbines.
column13: 11,718. Sayers, W. B. May 29. Gas turbines.-Elastic-fluid turbines are provided with rotors carrying longitudinal vanes co-operating with a series of guide passages in the casing so that motive fluid is caused to act repeatedly upon the rotor while flowing in a generally circumferential course. The guide passages increase progressively in axial dimensions to allow expansive working. Parts of the rotor may act as a turbine while other parts act simultaneously as a centrifugal fan for compressing fluids. In the case of an internalcombustion turbine, the fan part may compress the explosive mixture. A special method of setting and alining the shaft is described. A drum mounted on ball bearings is provided with a number of rows of buckets formed by circumferential and longitudinal ribs on the drum. In the outermost rows the buckets are of double pitch. Fluid is admitted by way of a nozzle j, and after acting on a vane rebounds into a guide passage k, which leads it to a bucket further in advance. The motive fluid continues to flow circumferentially round the rotor by passing into buckets and guide passages alternately until it finally reaches the exhaust. The nozzle j is arranged to coact with the central row a' of buckets, and the succeeding guide passages k increase in width to bring first a row of buckets a<2> into action, then a row a3, and so on, as shown in dotted lines in Fig. 1. More than one nozzle with its co-operating guide passages may be arranged round the periphery of the turbine. Where a single nozzle j is provided, the alining-device shown in Fig. 1 may be fitted. The apertures in the casing for the reception of the stuffing-boxes g have a small clearance, and are provided with adjusting- screws g<2>, by means of which the rotor may be advanced towards the inlet j. In a modification, the stator is provided with a duplicate set of guide passages k<1>, Fig. 3, arranged in a reverse direction, so that part of the apparatus acts as a turbine and part as a centrifugal pump. When used as an internal-combustion turbine, the pump portion is used to compress the explosive mixture. Explosion takes place in the first guide passage, which is fitted with a recess n<1> for the reception of an ignition device, or, alternatively, the ignition device may be situated in a cavity n communicating direct with the buckets. The distance between the delivery port of the pump section and the inlet end of the first guide passage is greater than the distance between adjacent rotor vanes, so that the rotor acts in itself as a cut-off valve for the intermittent supply of explosive mixture.

Method of selectively stripping an engine-run ceramic coating
column13: A process for selectively stripping a coating from a component of a turbomachine, and particularly a coating having a ceramic matrix that contains metallic particles dispersed therein that render the coating more difficult to remove from the component after the component has been subjected to elevated temperatures during operation of the turbomachine. The process generally includes immersing the component in an aqueous solution containing ferric chloride, nitric acid, and phosphoric acid, for a duration sufficient to attack the metallic particles in the coating. The component is then removed from the aqueous solution and its surface rinsed of the aqueous solution. The immersing and removing steps are then sequentially repeated a sufficient number of times to sufficiently attack the metallic particles to enable the coating to be mechanically removed from the component.

column13: 22,411. Sayers, W. B. Dec. 8. Electric railways and tramways with overhead supply conductors and return conductors in a slotted conduit. Conductors; conduits.-An insulated return conductor is placed in a conduit, and is earthed near the generator, transformer station, or other source of current, so that the difference of potential between the return and the conduit is limited to the drop in the return. Corrosion and electric disturbances are thus prevented. The conduit may be formed by the running rail a and a guard rail i of various forms, which may be connected by metal junction pieces a<1>, bedded on concrete &c., and furnished with boxes &c. t at intervals. Or the conduit may consist of a slotted pipe h as in Fig. 9. The conductor f may be held in an insulator g by the clamps o, o and set-screw q, Fig. 6, or by clamps 12, 13 and nut 14, Fig. 9, or may be soldered to a ring 19 clamped on an oil insulator, Fig. 12. Or, as shown in Fig. 11, it may consist of a strip f held on insulators secured by bolts passing through the sides of the conduit. The insulators may be screwed into one side of the conduit, or otherwise held therein The conductor is strained by the screw-carried roller v pulling in a loop at its end, Fig. 8, and it may be connected to feeders at intervals as at x. Collectors.-The brush 1, Fig. 6, for the return conductor and its insulating-shank 6 is supported by a hanger 2 under the influence of two springs. One spring, shown at 4, presses the brush on to the conductor, and the other allows the shank to turn up in case of obstruction.

column12: METHOD OF CONSTRUCTING SEPTIC SYSTEM INCLUDING PIPE SUPPORT
column13: A method includes placing pipe stands to support waste-conveying pipes in a trench in a septic system. The pipe stands are preferably flat bowtie-shaped sheets (preferably polymeric) folded to form stable pipe supports. Holes or notches are formed that align when the sheet is folded, thus providing stable support for a horizontal pipe when the panels' bottom edges rest on the ground. Modified versions include: folding a fold-out foot in the panels for engaging soft soil, forming fold-out dispersing flanges for dispersing waste dropped from the pipe, driving stakes into soft soil for stability, punching-out rings or multiple holes for supporting different sized pipes, stabilizing opposing panels in the sheet to fixedly maintain their spacing, forming a feature for receiving a grounded wire stake, and/or providing a bias from the living hinge of the fold line causing frictional gripping of the pipe. Many versions can be used in different orientations.

column12: Floating reference fault protection circuit for arc discharge lamp ballast
column13: A fault protection circuit for fluorescent lamp ballasts cuts off ballast power to the lamp in response to fast rise-time changes but not slower changes in either current output or voltage output of the ballast. The fault protection circuit is compatible with different ballast circuit topologies and features a floating reference level which renders the circuit insensitive to the lamp load wattage, making the circuit particularly useful in so-called universal ballasts.

column12: METHOD FOR REMOVING THERMAL BARRIER COATING
column13: PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide a method for removing a ceramic film, e.g. a thermal barrier coating(TBC) of yttria-stabilized zirconia(YSZ) from the surface of parts, e.g. gas turbine engine parts. SOLUTION: In this method, the ceramic film is exposed to an aqueous solution containing ammonium hydrogen fluoride and, if necessary, a wetting agent. The parts are, for example, immersed in the aqueous solution while being held at high temperature. By using this method, the ceramic film (18) can be completely removed from the parts (10) and a cooling hole without practically deteriorating a bond coat.

column12: VARIABLE HEIGHT BACKUP ASSEMBLY FOR ARTICULATING BOOTS
column13: A backup assembly is provided for backing up a seal assembly that seals a gap between two components of a joint assembly. The backup assembly may include an elastomer, a spring element embedded within the elastomer, and first and second rings located adjacent to the elastomer on opposite sides of the spring element. The spring element may be a garter spring, and the elastomer may be over-molded around the spring. The elastomer may have opposing wing extensions that extend respectively along the first and second rings, and the rings may be steel rings. The elastomer, spring element, and rings form an annular backup ring. The backup assembly may be employed in a seal assembly for sealing a gap between two components of a joint assembly. The seal assembly may include a diaphragm seal component, and the backup assembly operates to provide backup and extrusion resistance for the seal component.

column12: Output protection for arc discharge lamp ballast
column13: Output protection for arc discharge lamp ballasts is provided by applying sampled ballast current to a burden capacitor selected to present a low impedance across the winding to a substantially symmetrical waveform of the sample current. Asymmetry between the positive and negative half-cycles of the sample waveform, such as partial rectification caused by abnormal lamp operation, results in charge buildup across the capacitor. Sufficient charge buildup actuates a ballast disabling switch such as a silicon controlled rectifier.

115,509. Holt, W., and Brooks, B. May 22, 1917. Exciting.-To obtain a constant voltage or current from a self-regulating variable-speed dynamo, the cross-magnetization due to the armature load current is wholly or partially neutralized by means of a compensating winding on the field magnet, a closed winding or circuit is provided on the armature to produce a second cross-magnetization, and supplementary brushes are utilized for demagnetizing the main field-magnet poles. In one modification, Fig. 1, a separate short circuited armature winding b of high resistance and as non-inductive as possible produces by its rotation in the field of the main poles d a magnetic field received by supplementary poles c. The coils of the main armature winding which are under the poles e are spanned by two separated main and supplementary brushes f, f<1> which are electrically connected so as to produce a demagnetizing effect on the main poles d, as described in Specification 26880/10. Compensating-coils g are mounted on the poles e to neutralize or under or over compensate the field due to the load current. The salient poles c may be omitted by bringing the sides of the fieldmagnet yoke close to the armature; a few! series turns may be provided on the main poles d. Instead of directly short-circuiting the brushes f, f<1>, they may be connected through coils on the poles d; or the exciting-coils c may be connected across the main and supplementary brushes situated on opposite sides of a main pole d. The brushes f<1> may be placed under the poles d. The winding b may be joined through slip-rings to a variable resistance. In place of the alternating- current winding b, a second commutator winding b', Fig. 5, may be provided on the armature, having its brushes b<2> either short-circuited or connected through a resistance b<3>. In further modifications, the armature is provided with a single commutator winding, either having tappings connected through resistances as described in Specification 15686/13, or having the main brushes cross-connected through a resistance.

15,686. Brooks, B., and Holt, W. July 8. Exciting.-A self-regulating reversible variable-speed dynamo for giving a practically constant current-output is provided with shortcircuiting connexions e, f, g on the armature c, with or without interposed resistances e<1>, f<1>, g<1>, which give rise to a cross-field received by unwound poles situated between shunt-wound field-magnet poles a. The external current is taken off by brushes d, and sets up a field opposing that of the poles a and reducing the flux of these poles as the speed increases. Instead of using salient auxiliary poles j, the sides of the magnet frame may serve as auxiliary poles. The invention is applicable to multipolar dynamos. A few series turns may be placed upon the poles a or j to regulate the output.

A support walker comprising a horizontal rail having multiple sides in opposing orientations as track surfaces for a tracking carriage which traverses the rail. The tracking carriage circumscribes the rail and has pairs of radially disposed rollers mounted at the interior surfaces of the carriage in positions such that the pairs of rollers are in opposing contact with opposing track surfaces of the rail. The tracking carriage is thereby restricted to parallel movement in relation to the rail, with minimal play in a radial direction. A restraining vest is coupled to the tracking carriage by straps which connect at front, back and side sections of the vest. The vest further includes rigid stays which assist in maintaining the patient in upright orientation during therapy.

The present application relates generally to carrier bags, and specifically to a reconfigurable bag which can carry a car seat. The carrier of the present application includes a wall system defining a seat compartment, the wall system moveable between an extended configuration, in which an expansion portion is included in defining an outer wall of the seat compartment, and a retracted configuration, in which the expansion portion is excluded from defining the outer wall of the seat compartment. The outer wall of the seat compartment further has an opening, the opening permitting objects to enter or exit the seat compartment and the outer wall of the seat compartment having a cover portion being moveable to close the opening. The carrier further includes a releasable fastener system to govern access through the opening. A related method of utilizing the carrier as a car seat carrier and backpack are also described.

column13: 29,361. Brooks, B., and Holt, W. Dec. 20. Starting prime-movers, dynamo-electric machines with control circuits for.-The dynamo electric machine of a combined enging starting and lighting system is provided with two independent armature windings connected to the same commutator and a field-magnet system controlled by one or more switches in such a manner that the machine runs with a different number of poles when acting as a motor than when acting as a generator. In the arrangement shown in Fig. 2, the machine runs as a two-pole generator and as a four-pole motor, and is provided with a two-pole armature winding a and a four-pole armature winding c connected to the same commutator, having three brushes b, b<1>, b<2>. The field-magnet system has four poles d, d', d', d<3> alternately wound with shunt and series coils e, f controlled by a switch g. In the modification shown in Fig. 3, the machine when running as a dynamo is made selfregulating by short-circuiting the armature coils under the poles d, d<3>, or by connecting the brushes b<1>, b<2> through an adjustable resistance j by means of the switch g. A fourth brush b<3> and resistance k may be added. The brushes b<1>, b<2> may also be connected through coils which de-magnetize the main poles, or through coils which oppose or assist the armature cross-magnetization. In the modification shown in Fig. 4, self regulation is obtained by shortcircuiting the brusbes b<2>, b<3> by means of a s cond switch g<1> mechanically connected to the switch g. In a further modification, the switch g controls the circuit of the series coils f, and the switch g' the circuit of the shunt coils e. Shunt and series coils may be placed on all the poles, and the machine may operate as a series, shunt, or compound wound motor. The brushes common to both windings a, c may be replaced by separate brushes. Specification 26,880/10, [Class 35, Dynamo-electric generators &c.], is referred to.

Switches.-Relates to switches having a rotary barrel formed with a number of flat faces adapted to bear upon spring contact fingers, the barrel being thus retained in different positions for the purpose of making different circuit connexions for lamps on a motorvehicle or the like. According to the invention, the barrel is made of metal and has pieces of insulating-material let into the flat faces. A solid metal barrel 1 operated by a handle 11 and having five flat faces inlaid with the requisite pieces of insulating-material co-operates with a.row of spring contact fingers 6 to control the head, side, and tail lamps and the cutting in and out of the dynamo in a motor-car lighting system. The current is led in through the spindle 2 by means of a terminal on the bearing 3, and is led out by terminals on the different contact fingers. An indicating-drum 7 is held frictionally against and turns with the barrel 1, the indications being visible through a window. A tubular barrel may be employed instead of the solid barrel 1.

A method and apparatus for an incipient fire detection system that receives gaseous samples and measures the light absorption spectrum of the mixture of gases evolving from heated combustibles includes a detector for receiving gaseous samples and subjecting the samples to spectroscopy and determining wavelengths of absorption of the gaseous samples. The wavelengths of absorption of the gaseous samples are compared to predetermined absorption wavelengths. A warning signal is generated whenever the wavelengths of absorption of the gaseous samples correspond to the predetermined absorption wavelengths. The method includes receiving gaseous samples, subjecting the samples to light spectroscopy, determining wavelengths of absorption of the gaseous samples, comparing the wavelengths of absorption of the gaseous samples to predetermined absorption wavelengths and generating a warning signal whenever the wavelengths of absorption of the gaseous samples correspond to the predetermined absorption wavelengths. In an alternate embodiment, the apparatus includes a series of channels fluidically connected to a plurality of remote locations. A pump is connected to the channels for drawing gaseous samples into the channels. A detector is connected to the channels for receiving the drawn gaseous samples and subjecting the samples to spectroscopy. The wavelengths of absorption are determined and compared to predetermined absorption wavelengths is provided. A warning signal is generated whenever the wavelengths correspond.

column13: A cover, removably mounted in a recess at one end of a cigarette lighter body, permits access to lighter service points within the recess. The cover includes an integral member formed of a plastics material and having a plate-like body consisting of a first section hinged to a second section by a reduced thickness section of the body. Projections extend from the first section of the body for releasably holding it within the recess. A hollow cylindrical spigot extends from the second section and is secured into the recess by a bayonet-like connection. By lifting the first section out of the recess it can be displaced angularly about its hinged connection to the second section and access can be obtained to the part of the recess covered by the first section. If necessary, the second section can be removed by twisting the plate-like body to open the bayonet-like connection with the lighter body. A spring is fitted into the spigot on the second section for biasing a lighter part, such as a battery, to the lighter.

The system and method for an additively manufactured self-destructive delay device is a bellow/lattice structure or other form. The device may be installed as a replacement to a previous device, where the device yields under the deployment force at a specific rate to match the time-displacement curve established by a previous hydraulic delay device. The delay device has a virtually unlimited lifespan, is cheap to manufacture, and can be adaptable to other loads and conditions for use in or on other platforms. This solution can be applied anywhere where mechanical delay devices are needed within systems. Some examples include wing/fin deployment mechanisms, safety crumple zones, or devices that act as shear pins.

[Cognate Application, 7950/14.] Turning-gear.-The armature shaft 2 of an electric starting-motor is ex tended and screwed, a pinion 3 acting as a nut on the thread. The pinion carries a robber disk 10, and is normally free from teeth 9 fixed or formed on the fly-wheel. When the motor is started, inertia of the pinion is sufficient to cause it to move axially until the disk bears on the fly-wheel; the friction between the disk and the fly - wheel then causes complete engagement of the pinion. A spring 5 acts as a buffer to the axial movement of the pinion. When the engine picks up speed, the pinion being moved out of gear, a light torsion spring 12 assists to keep the pinion disengaged. In a modification the screw-threads are replaced by a block 14, Fig. 4, on a shaft on which a pinion is fixed and a groove 15 in the armature shaft. When the electric motor is to be used as a generator, a friction-wheel 10, Fig. 4, integral with the pinion may be used to co-act with the wheel 19 on the engine shaft. The pinion may have worm teeth -or be replaced by a friction-wheel. Specification 4817/14 is referred to.

column12: Microprocessor controlled security system for computers
column13: A microprocessor controlled computer security system is disclosed that provides for controlled access to single or multiple components of a computer system. The security system includes a magnetic card reading and encoding device that reads component access and time allotment data from a magnetically encoded card. A microcontroller, which incorporates a microprocessor, processes the data read by the reading and encoding device and responsively issues enable or disable signals through a component interface circuit to the computer system component or components to be enabled or disabled. The components to be enabled may be the video display device, hard disk drive, or external central processing units of slave computers. The security system further includes audio and visual indicators that provide system and component status information. The magnetic card reading and encoding device is operable in a program mode, wherein the magnetic card is programmed with component access and time data, and a reading mode wherein the reading and encoding device reads and updates the access and time data on the card.

column12: METHOD OF AND APPARATUS FOR PRODUCING TUBULAR ARTICLES OF BIAXIALLY ORIENTED POLYMERS.
column13: Un procédé de production d'un article tubulaire tel qu'un corps de boîte ou une bouteille, avec un polymère thermoplastique cristallisable à orientation biaxiale tel que le téréphthalate de polyéthylène à partir d'un article tubulaire de plus petites dimensions, tel qu'une préforme, ayant au moins une extrémité ouverte, consiste à chauffer l'article tubulaire plus petit jusqu'à atteindre une température supérieure à la température de transition du verre mais inférieure à la température de fusion du polymère, à attirer l'article tubulaire axialement par des moyens mécaniques tels qu'une tige poussoir d'extension (122) ou un élément de mandrin d'étirage, et à étirer simultanément ou séquentiellement l'article tubulaire dans le sens axial et dans le sens transversal par une pression d'un fluide interne introduit par l'extrémité ouverte (13), sans l'utilisation d'un moule externe ou autre contrainte extérieure. L'article étiré et orienté biaxialement (10) peut être chauffé ultérieurement pour recuire le polymère, puis il est refroidi avant d'être retiré de l'appareil d'étirage, la pression interne étant réduite pendant le recuit et le refroidissement. Pour le téréphthalate de polyéthylène, la température d'étirage est comprise entre 75oC et 120oC et la pression du fluide interne est comprise entre 7 et 15 bars, tandis que la température de recuit est comprise entre 110oC et 240oC et la pression du fluide interne réduite utilisée pendant le recuit et/ou le refroidissement est comprise entre 2 et 4 bars.

Control and output-quality variables of a process plant (1) are plotted against parallel axes in a display unit (7). New variable-values for process optimization are fixed for the variables taken in turn, each selection being made within displayed ranges (Rn-Rn) derived from the hulls effective between the respective variable and the variables already fixed. A display unit (13) provides on-line parallel-axis display of variable-values from the plant (1), showing alarm carets (DC, UC) where values violate limits (UL, LL) determined by the convex hulls, and allowing variation in the displayed-value for observing the resultant effect in avoiding alarm situation and towards optimization.

The member 14 has a cam surface 17, made resilient by a cut 24, co-operating with the stem of the valve 23. Finger piece 11 has an integral spring 12 and a spigot 13 engaged in a groove, Fig. 3, not shown, in the underside of member 14. Body 1 has a base 2 with a filling valve 2a and has a plate 21 mounted by a screw 22 to hold the flint wheel, flint &c. in position, the end of spring 8a engaging in a recess 26 in this plate so that on rotation of the plate to expose the flint the spring pressure is relieved. In operation, fingerpiece 11 is pivoted toward body 1 and causes, through spigot 13, member 14 and wheel 20 to rotate, the cam surface 17 moving off the burner to allow the valve stem to rise. column12: Improvements in and relating to Dynamo-electric Machines.
column13: 22,053. Martin, W. C., Lowson, J., [trading as Martin & Co., W. C.], and Sayers, W. B. Oct. 13. Casings.-Consists in encasing the rotating parts of dynamo-electric machines, for use on board ship &c., within a system of overlapping plates, rings, and abutments so arranged that, while allowing efficient ventilation to take place, any liquid &c. which may enter is confined to the casing and is drained out again. The armature 1, Fig. 1, rotates within a fixed field magnet 2 having an annular yoke 3 to which are screwed rings 4 having outwardly-facing channels 4<a>. Plates 6 curved inwardly at their peripheries are secured to and overlap the rings 4, and their lower parts are perforated for the escape of liquid. Abutments 9 situated opposite to the central openings 8 in the plates 6 are cast integral with the rings 4 and bearings 11 for the armature shaft 12. In a modification, the channel 4<a> of each ring faces inwardly, overlapping the corresponding plate 6, and is itself perforated, the abutments 9 being formed as flanges on the pedestal bearings. In another modification, in order to cause the air entering or leaving by the passages 7, 8 to take a more or less sinuous path, each ring 4 is provided with three channels at its periphery, the outermost of which faces inwardly while the other two face outwardly, and the adjacent plate 6 is formed with two inwardly-curved projections which enter into the recesses thus produced in the ring 4 ; the abutments 9 and the edges of the plates 6 around the passages 8 are also formed with mutuallyoverlapping projections, the yoke being perforated in this modification. In all cases, the plates 6 are made in halves to facilitate access to the interior of the machine. The shaft 12 may have attached at one end a fan device 13, Fig. 5, which is adapted to draw in air through the opposite end of the machine and to expel it through the adjacent opening 7. One of the abutments 9 is fixed to the fan device, and the upper half of one or both of the plates 6 is hinged at 6<c> to the adjacent ring 4.

NITISINONE FOR TREATMENT OF OCULOCUTANEOUS/OCULAR ALBINISM AND FOR INCREASING PIGMENTATION
column13: A method is provided for the treatment of vision problems in a subject suffering from one of various forms of albinism, including, for example, oculocutaneous albinism types OCA1a and OCA1b, as well as ocular albinism type 1, resulting from mutations in the GPR143 gene, as well as the OCA2, OCA3 or OCA4 genes, by administering to the subject a pharmaceutical composition comprising a therapeutically effective amount of the compound (2-[2-nitro-4-(trifluoromethyl)benzoyl]cyclohexane-l,3-dione), also known as NTBC for a sufficient period of time. The administration of NTBC is believed to increase the amount of pigmentation in the subject and alleviate certain symptoms caused by lack of pigmentation in the eye tissues. Also described are methods of use of NTBC for increasing the pigmentation of a subject for cosmetic purposes, by administering to the subject a therapeutically effective amount of NTBC.

column12: Adaptive RF signal filter using acousto-optic spectrum analyzer and re-writable XDM mask
column13: A coherent wideband acousto-optic RF spectrum analyzer for processing an input RF signal, having a CW laser providing a first laser beam, a Bragg cell used in a deflection mode with the laser beam incident thereon and receiving the input RF signal, and in response thereto producing multiple diffracted modulated light beams, a Fourier Transform lens with the modulated light beams incident thereon and in response thereto producing optical signal beams producing a Fourier Transform image in an image plane spaced apart from the Fourier Transform lens, and a photosensitive, optically re-writable medium positioned in the image plane with the optical signal beams incident thereon, the medium having an optical distribution pattern to function as a mask to attenuate a selected portion of the RF spectrum of the optical signal beams and produce an attenuated optical beam.

column12: Improvements relating to heat treatment using microwave electromagnetic radiation
column13: 1,039,224. Microwave heating apparatus. ELLIOTT ELECTRONIC TUBES Ltd. March 18, 1964 [March 27, 1963], No. 12052/63. Heading H5H. Laminar material 51, e.g. paper, is heated by conveying it on a plate 52 past a member 53 which is connected to a microwave energy source, at the resonant frequency of the member, by a coaxial feeder or waveguide, the plate 52 being earthed. The arrangement relies on strip line conduction, a travelling wave field being established between the members 52, 53 which are of non-magnetic electrically-conducting metal. The field may be made monotonic by using a matched load at the end of members 52, 53 instead of an open or short-circuit. Member 52 may be replaced by a roller 54, Fig. 2 (not shown), and member 53 by a generally U-shaped waveguide 55, which opens out on the strip 51 and has a ridge 55b projecting from its base for concentrating the energy, Fig. 3 (not shown). Members 52, 54 may be replaced by metal strip or foil.

column13: A method for volume-selected NMR spectroscopy where an rf pulse of selected bandwidth, in the presence of a field gradient superimposed upon an initial homogenous magnetic field, rotates a slice of magnetization into the transverse plane, and it then uses a high power refocussing pulse to refocus the phase roll that accompanies the rf pulse. After an appropriate time, the magnetization is pulsed back to the homogenous magnetic field axis and the gradient collapsed. A read pulse is used to tip the magnetization of interest into the transverse plane for acquisition in the absence of applied gradients.

A gift certificate dispensing device having an internal machine-readable indicia reader is disclosed for printing and dispensing a certificate either based upon payment by a user or upon the insertion of a prepaid form into a slot in communication with the scanner. A plurality of gift certificate dispensing devices can be connected in a network under the control of a central processing unit. column13: A ground fault isolation system (100) and ground fault isolation circuit for isolating ground faults in electrical subsea conductor lines. Operation of a multi-variable process involves multidimensional representati on of the values (pl-p12) of the process variables (Pl-P12) according to individual coordinate axes, and an operational envelope (UB,LB) derived from a group of sets of values for the process and quality variables (P1-P12,Q1-Q2) accumulated from multiple, earlier operations of the process, defines an operating zone for the process and quality variables of the process. If the current value (p7) of any process variable (P7) goes outside the envelope, a n envelope (UO,LB) for a different, wider grouping of the stored data-sets is displayed at least for the quality variables (Ql-Q2). A series of nested envelopes to provide stepwise enlargement of the operating zone may be provided, but non-nested envelopes can be used where there is clustering of acceptable values of process variables of the stored data-sets. The changes to control variables to bring the values of dependent variables within a best operating range can be determined.

INTERRUPT LEVEL SHARING CIRCUIT AND METHOD
column13: An interrupt interface circuit for interrupt level sharing comprising a pulse generator (36, 38) having an open-collector or tri-state output (40) connected to an external interrupt line shared by other similar circuits. An active internal interrupt signal (Card Unit) causes the pulse generator to pulse. The external interrupt line is fed back and latched on a disabling input of the pulse generator so that any pulse on the external interrrupt line prevents further pulsing. The software handler of the interrupt, upon servicing an interrupt of the interrupt level, causes the enabling of the pulse generator of that level, thereby permitting active internal interrupt signals to produce a further pulse. By this interrupt level sharing, phantom interrupts are eliminated and servicing overhead is minimized.

The α- haloalkyl-arene may have the general formula wherein n is an integer from 1 to 4 and each R independently represents hydrogen on an alkyl group having 1 to 4 carbon atoms, the arene nucleus is preferably a benzene ring which is preferably substituted in at least one position ortho to the CR 2 groups. An optical memory system for storage and retrieval of digital data using a source of writing light in the visible light range and a separate source of near infrared, polarized reading light. The writing light is amplitude modulated by a signal containing the digital data to be stored. Horizontal and vertical deflectors deflect the beams to scan horizontally and vertically in response to control signals. The scanning beams are focused to a focal point to impinge upon a stationary medium manufactured of a dry film having submicron electrically photosensitive particles embedded in a thermoplastic layer mounted on a substantially transparent electrically conductive substrate. The particles are insensitive to light at the reading light wavelength. The particles are initially uncharged and the film is sensitive to light after receiving an initial surface charge. The regions of the medium with the charged particles and with the uncharged particles cause differing angular rotation of the electric and magnetic field vectors of the reading light, with the degree of rotation of the reading light after passing through the medium indicating whether a digital data bit of one or zero is recorded. A fixed mask is positioned in the focal plane of the lens and in juxtaposition with the medium. The mask is opaque to the writing and reading light beams and has a matrix of rows and columns of transparent apertures. The apertures define the extent of the regions of the medium with the charged and uncharged particles. A Senarmont polarization compensator is positioned to be exposed to the reading light beam after passing through the mask apertures and the medium and is responsive only to the incident of the reading light thereon. The compensator detects the angular rotation of the fields by measuring the reading light beam intensity and relating it to a   predetermined reference, and modulates the amplitude of an indicator signal from a photodiode so as to produce an output signal if rotation is detected indicative of a recorded information bit of stored digital data at a one or a zero binary state. Related control circuitry provides the scan control signals, and a heatable erasure pad selectively erases portions of the medium.

column13: "MéTODO PARA REMOVER DEPóSITOS DO MOTOR EM COMPONENTES DE TURBINA E COMPOSIçãO PARA USO NO MESMO". é descrito um método e uma composição de limpeza para remover depósitos do motor (58) em componentes de turbina (10), em particular em discos de turbina (10) e em eixos de turbina (10). Este método compreende as seguintes etapas: (a) fornecer um componente de turbina (10) apresentando um superfície (14) com depósitos do motor (58) sobre esta, sendo que o componente de turbina (10) compreende um metal de base (50) contendo níquel e/ou cobalto; e (b) tratar a superfície (14) do componente de turbina (10) com uma composição de limpeza para converter os depósitos de motor (58) nesta em uma mancha removível sem substancialmente atacar quimicamente o metal de base (50) do componente de turbina (10). A composição de limpeza compreende uma solução aquosa que é substancialmente livre de ácido acético e que compreende: uma fonte de íon nitrato em uma quantidade, em peso do íon nitrato, de cerca de 470 a cerca de 710 gramas/litro; e uma fonte de íon bifluoreto em uma quantidade, em peso do íon bifluoreto, de cerca de 0,5 a cerca de 15 gramas/litro. A mancha que é formada pode ser removida da superfície (14) do componente de turbina (10) de uma forma que não altere substancialmente a superfície (14) deste.

Control and output-quality variables of a process plant (1) are plotted against parallel axes in a display unit (7). Convex hulls between pairs of variables are calculated from sets of the variable-values accumulated historically in stores (7, 9) during successive runs of the process, and hulls (HH; TC, BC) between successive axis-pairs are displayed. New variable-values for process optimization are fixed for the variables taken in turn, each selection being made within displayed ranges (Rn-Rn) derived from the hulls effective between the respective variable and the variables already fixed. A display unit (13) provides on-line parallel-axis display of variable-values from the plant (1), showing alarm carets (DC, UC) where values violate limits (UL, LL) determined by the convex hulls, and allowing variation in the displayed-value for observing the resultant effect in avoiding alarm situation and towards optimization.

column13: A method is provided for the treatment of vision problems in a subject suffering from one of various forms of albinism, including, for example, oculocutaneous albinism types OCA1a and OCA1b, as well as ocular albinism type 1, resulting from mutations in the GPR143 gene, as well as the OCA2, OCA3 or OCA4 genes, by administering to the subject a pharmaceutical composition comprising a therapeutically effective amount of the compound (2-[2-nitro-4-(trifluoromethyl)benzoyl]cyclohexane-l,3-dione), also known as NTBC for a sufficient period of time. The administration of NTBC is believed to increase the amount of pigmentation in the subject and alleviate certain symptoms caused by lack of pigmentation in the eye tissues. Also described are methods of use of NTBC for increasing the pigmentation of a subject for cosmetic purposes, by administering to the subject a therapeutically effective amount of NTBC.

Control of a multi-variable process involves multi¬ dimensional representation of the values (Qa-Qh) of the process variables {a-h) according to individual coordinate axes (Xa-Xh) , and response based on sets of historical values for the process-variables accumulated from multiple, earlier operations of the process. An envelope (UL-LL) showing the best operating zone ( ΛBOZ' ) for each process variable due to the current values of the other variables is calculated from the accumulated historical values, and alarm conditions in which the current value of a variable lies outside the BOZ is rectified by operator- or automated-change of the values (Qa-Qc) of manipulatable variables {a-c) . Targets for the variables are achieved, alarms rectified and value optimisation realised using an inner envelope (UI-LI) derived from a subset of the BOZ- defining set of historical values. Where the alarm rate is low, improved operation is obtained by narrowing down the BOZ set so as to tighten the BOZ envelope (UL-LL) to establish an inner envelope where alarm rate remains acceptable, as a new BOZ.

column13: An optical communications system is disclosed. In the optical communications system, a received light source is modulated in accordance with an electrical signal using an acousto-optic modulator. The acousto-optic modulator modulates an amplitude of the received light source in accordance with an amplitude of the electrical signal. Furthermore, an angle of diffraction of a beam produced by the acousto-optic modulator is a function of a frequency of the electrical signal. The optical communications system is equipped with a waveplate that converts a polarization of the diffracted beam to correspond to the polarization of an undiffracted beam. Improved detection and recovery of the electrical signal may be achieved due to the polarization correspondence between the diffracted beam and the undiffracted beam.
